Eyewear Industry:

Eyewear is a massive $100 billion+ industry that is expected to surpass $140 billion by 2020. This means the eyewear industry is on track to grow at 8% yearly. Unbelievable growth for such a large industry.

The industry is dominated by Luxottica. This vertically integrated company designs, manufactures, and retails its eyewear brands. It also makes the eyewear for leading designer brands.

Some of Luxottica’s own brands and retail stores include: Oakley, Ray-Ban, Sunglass Hut, LensCrafters, Pearle Vision, Target Optical, Sears Optical, and more.

Luxcottica is the largest optical retailer in the United States with 7.3% of U.S. retail sales in 2015.

Some of Luxottica’s luxury partners include: Prada, Coach, Giorgio Armani, Michael Kors, Chanel, Ralph Lauren, Versace, and more.

Luxottica is the largest company in the industry with worldwide marketshare is estimated at 14%, the second largest company being Essilor at 13%.

In October 2018 Luxottica and Essilor merged into a single company. This merger into EssilorLuxotica now occupies almost 30% of the worldwide marketshare of eyewear industry, and sells almost a billion lenses and frames annually.

The eyewear industry is controlled by a monopoly. This monopoly keeps prices of eyewear inflated and manipulates the industry to suit their needs and greed.

Sun is Bad

The National Eye Institute, as part of the federal government’s National Institutes of Health (NIH), stresses the need for wearing sunglasses.

This authority figure states that sunglasses protect the eyes from the sun’s ultraviolet rays. Failure to protect from these UV rays:
- Cataracts: a clouding of the eye’s lens that can blur vision. An estimated 20% of cases are caused by extended UV exposure.
- Macular degeneration, resulting from damage to the retina that destroys central vision. Macular degeneration is the leading cause of blindness in the United States.
- Pterygium, a tissue growth over the white part of the surface of the eye that can alter the curve of the eyeball, causing astigmatism.

Macular degeneration is the leading cause of blindness in the United States. An estimated more than 10 million Americans are impacted by this cause of vision loss. Macular Degeneration is caused by the deterioration of the central portion of the retina. This central portion is responsible for focusing central vision in the eyes, and controls our ability to do anything important visually.

The causes of macular degeneration are still not known, but the treatment to reducing the risk of macular degeneration is changes in diet, avoiding smoking and protecting eyes from ultraviolet light.

It is insane that nobody understands the leading cause of blindness in the United States and continue to push the idea that getting ultraviolet light from the sun is harmful to the eyes.

Most eye sight problems in modern society are due to over reliance on glasses and lack of sunlight hitting the eyes.

Regardless the National Eye Institute, National Institutes of Health, Ophthalmologists, and many other authority figures continue to stress and scare the public into believing that sunlight is harmful for the eyes. Eye sight and problems with eyes continues to worsen as the use of sunglasses and eyewear continues to skyrocket. Sun is Healthy

John Ott is a photo-researcher and author of Health and Light that made a living out of a hobby of time-lapse photography. He began to capture the movements of nature by setting up a camera that would be constantly taking pictures throughout a long period of time. For the human eye we take for granted nature and don’t realize how alive plants are and their movements. In his time-lapse photography he was able to show how lively plants are and their development along months of photographs. His interest in the field led him to do work for films that wanted to capture the movement of plants and nature. John began to experiment with various lighting and strategies on how to get plants to move and grow in the direction that he wanted them to form. These experiments led him to make surprising discoveries into how important lighting was for the growth of plants.

He noticed that different types of light and lighting conditions ranging from unfiltered sunlight to various kinds of artificial light had vastly different effects on the growth, development and motion of plants.

Eventually his interests in this field had him experiment with rats and various other animals. This is when he realized the profound impact that light had on animals and it led him to realize the profound impact it had on humans.

One experiment was done on minks. There was a mink breeder that heard about John’s work and wanted to know how she can apply his concepts to breeding minks. She was having trouble with minks reproducing and there were too many males being born. She wanted more females and more reproduction which would increase the ability to breed more minks.

In the experiment John had the light changed that was on the minks. He put pink and blue glass. In the pink glass the minks became more aggressive and hostile. This change in nature also led them to be physically weaker and overall the minks were unable to reproduce. Most of the minks died. In the blue glass the minks became friendly and docile. This change led the minks to be healthier and reproduce in vast numbers. Most of the minks lived long.

Observe females that wear pink/red glasses and notice how they act and function. You will notice that they are usually crazy, aggressive, and act in an erratic nature. This is the influence that pink glass is having on their psyche.

Observe males that wear blue glasses and notice they act and function. You will notice they are docile and kind. Sometimes to the point where you wonder what the hell this person took to be so nice. It’s the blue glass having an effect on their psyche.

Experiments such as these that John ran for many years showed the radical changes in both mental and physical health of animals solely based on the lighting that the animals received.

Plants, and animals are vastly different and yet extremely similar.

The basic principles of photosynthesis which provides energy to plants via sunlight do carry over from plant life into animal life. The processes are different and animal life is greatly improved, but the foundation is the same.

There was even a company that changed the lights to be full spectrum. Full spectrum lights provide the whole spectrum of light which is most closely aligned to the sunlight. The productivity of the company rose 25% after the installation of these lights. This is absolutely insane and provides evidence of the importance of lighting both at home, at work, and all around us.

You might be negatively impacted by the lights in your work, and at your home. Full spectrum lighting is the way to go and having that implemented where you work would significantly boost productivity and overall employee satisfaction.

Light plays an important role in plants as it does in animals, as it does in humans.

The role of light still has to be studied, but some great insights were made by John Ott in his experimentation and dealings with human beings.

Glandular System

The endocrine system is made up of glands that produce and secrete hormones. These hormones are chemical substances produced in the body that regulate the activity of cells and organs. Hormones regulate the body’s growth, metabolism, sexual development and function. Hormones are released into the bloodstream and affect several organs throughout the body.

Hormones are chemical messengers created by the body. They transfer information between cells to coordinate the functions of various parts of the body.

The glands that make up the endocrine system include hypothalamus, thyroid, pituitary, parathyroids, adrenals, pineal, and reproductive organs.

The endocrine system is extremely important to the overall functioning of the human body and a disruption in the endocrine system can create many of the diseases that are rampant in today’s society.

The entire glandular system can be affected, or glandular actions modified, by light received through the eyes.

This is why John Ott found such profound changes in the behavior and makeup of humans that were exposed to plenty of sunlight throughout the day as opposed to humans that worked in the basement and never got any sun. The former was healthy and active, while the latter was weak and unhealthy.

The eyes contain photosensitive cells in its retina. These photosensitive cells have connections directly to the pituitary gland in the brain. Stimulation of these cells comes from sunlight, such photo-receptors play a vital role in human physiology and health, a study by Dr.’s Turner and Mainster of the University of Kansas School of Medicine, published in the British Journal of Opthamology in 2008.

The effects of these photoreceptors and photosensitive cells are not only in the brain, but the whole body.

The proper functioning of the endocrine system relies on sunlight entering the eyes and the body being exposed to the sun. Failure to do this creates disruption within the endocrine system which can have significant impacts in various facets of one’s life. Physiological and psychological impacts are had from malfunctioning of any of the glands in the endocrine system.

Sun stimulation is directly tied to the proper functioning of the endocrine system. The endocrine system is the system that produces and secretes hormones that regulate the activity of cells and organs.

Any disruption in this and you can expect the activity of cells and organs to malfunction.

Animals respond to the intensity, periodicity, and wavelength distribution of light in much of the same way that plants do.
